5 Sec. 534. A general primary of all political parties except as
6 provided in sections 532 and 685 must be held in every election
7 precinct in this state on the Tuesday after the first Monday in
8 August before every general November election, at which time the
9 qualified and registered voters of each political party may vote
10 for party candidates for the office of governor, United States
11 Senator, Representative in Congress, state senator, representative
12 in the legislature, county executive, prosecuting attorney,
13 sheriff, county clerk, county treasurer, register of deeds, drain
14 commissioner, public works commissioner, county road commissioner,
15 county mine inspector, surveyor, and candidates for office in
16 townships, and candidates for school board member of a local school
17 district. A nomination for an office must be made only if the
18 official is to be elected at the next succeeding general November
19 election.
20 Sec. 697. At the general November election, the names of the
21 several offices to be voted for must be placed on the ballot
22 substantially in the following order in the years in which
23 elections for those offices are held: Electors of President and
24 Vice President of the United States; governor and lieutenant
25 governor; secretary of state; attorney general; United States
26 Senator; Representative in Congress; senator and representative in
27 the state legislature; members of the state board of education;
28 regents of the University of Michigan; trustees of Michigan State
29 University; governors of Wayne State University; county executive;
STM H02152'25 (H-1) 3bm7kr

6
1 prosecuting attorney; sheriff; clerk; treasurer; register of deeds;
2 mine inspector in counties electing a mine inspector; county road
3 commissioners; drain commissioners; coroners; and surveyor. The
4 following township officers must be placed on the same ballot as
5 above described in substantially the following order in the year in
6 which elections for those offices are held: supervisor, clerk,
7 treasurer, trustees, and constables. In addition, the office of
8 local school district board member must be placed on the same
9 ballot as above in the year in which an election for that office is
10 held.
11 Sec. 699. At any regular election, the names of the several
12 nonpartisan offices to be voted for shall must be placed on a
13 separate portion of the ballot containing no party designation in
14 the following order: justices of the supreme court, judges of the
15 court of appeals, judges of the circuit court, judges of the
16 probate court, judges of the district court, community college
17 board of trustees member, intermediate school district board
18 member, city officers, the following village officers in
19 substantially the following order in the year in which elections
20 for the offices are held: president, clerk, treasurer, and
21 trustees, and in a year in which an election for the office is
22 held, local school district board member, metropolitan district
23 officer , and district library board member.
